Imagine a very long webpage with many sections (for example, a single-page HTML specification). If a user requests a specific section of it (for example, page.html#section7), can the Web server first transmit that section, and then transmit the other sections?
Streaming order:
1. The beginning of the HTML document, up to the <body> tag
2. The HTML code for section 7
3. The HTML code for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser needs to ensure that sections 1 to 6 are inserted above section 7 on the webpage.
Is this reasonable? Would it be useful?
The goal I want to achieve is to have the linked section (#section7) rendered as quickly as possible, without having to reimplement it using JavaScript or similar. I want a very long HTML document, but where the linked sections can still be rendered as quickly as possible. It should be achievable with just HTML.
The content can be streamed like this, and the browser will insert each <contents> element into the corresponding <div> element.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
Although the streaming order is out of sequence, the browser will assemble the HTML document in order.
@user22 Actually, it's possible to reorder document content without using JS. However, if you want the server to do something, you can't use the URL hash part anymore, but instead use query string parameters to let the server know which part you want to see first. As for reordering the page content, you have the following options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use templates with slots
@user23 That's right. The issue is that the visual order (what the user sees) and the DOM order are inconsistent. If HTML could support out-of-order streaming, while the browser arranges the content in order within the DOM, it might be very useful.
However, the slot method seems promising. I'll give it a try.
@user22 Oh, you want the browser to automatically fix the DOM order?
@user23 Exactly, that's what I'm thinking. The only reason for transmitting section 7 first is to let the user see it as soon as possible. If this could be achieved without affecting the DOM order, that would be great, so the browser could ensure the final DOM order and visual order are consistent.
In other words, transmit section 7 first, but the final result (DOM and visual appearance) should be exactly the same as if all sections were transmitted in order.
@user22 @user33 You can take a look at PHOOOS which doesn't use JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
